    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Health Insurance Taxes</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dr Gary Sole letter holds income tax deductibility of health insurance for self-employed people would benefit everyone</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Senseless Health Deduction'' (editorial, Oct. 14):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Senseless Health Deduction'' (editorial, Oct. 14):</p>
        <p>Income tax deductibility of health insurance for self-employed people would benefit everyone.</p>
        <p>With 43 million people uninsured, there is a flaw in the system that cries out for correction. Most of the insured have plans of limited flexibility that their employers provide. These plans usually offer a full range of benefits that come at a very high premium. This leaves self-employed and unemployed people a limited number of plans to choose from, almost all with high premiums.</p>
        <p>If the tax treatment is made more equitable, people employed by corporations would have no tax incentive to accept the plan provided by their employers. This would open up an entirely new market with a variety of plans at varying prices that would give consumers an extensive choice of health insurance options.</p>
        <p>GARY SOLE, M.D.  Bloomfield Hills, Mich., Oct. 16, 2000</p>
      </block>
